text: So first of all, I understand your point that the SMA feels like a throwback. What I would say is that in the current market, particularly in the wealth channel, it's not that there aren't SMAs. There are many, many SMA strategies. It's just that SMAs are now being used where they're needed for investment merit. So why would you have an SMA of large cap equity? That doesn't make any sense. You can go buy an ETF. There's no problem with turnover or liquidity or pricing. It's easy to make markets on. It's easy to distribute. Depending on the strategy, there are many things that are much better suited for other rappers. But there are things that are for their own investment reasons, like risk mitigating strategies or many derivative strategies, or even tax loss harvesting for that matter, where SMA strategies or places where you need lots of customization, like direct indexing, where you had a real compelling need for direct indexing. Those do get implemented via SMA. And in fact, every... Every major custodian in the United States has SMA support and platforms and programs to cope with those managers. But here's the thing about the SMA. The SMA is not ideal for the investment manager in a couple ways. The first being distribution. It's harder to onboard and just get SMA clients up and running. Right? Right. Right. Right. Right. Right. And you like my ETF, that afternoon, you can get on your trading platform and allocate to it. Right? You don't need to ask anybody's permission. Well, I mean, some platforms maybe you do. But for the most part, all the plumbing, it's all there. Right? SMAs are different. The SMA manager has to be able to act on that platform. There's a bit of due diligence that's going to have to be done. The actual positions themselves are in the client's portfolio. So that has some implications. Right? Right. And that's a harder thing to distribute. Right? And the reality is that our business comes down to easy distribution. So SMAs are not great for distribution for the manager. But more importantly, they're harder on the operations side. If I run a hedge fund or any commingled vehicle for that matter, I have one big pool of assets. Right? And then the legal structure, 40 Act, 3C7 fund, note, whatever it is. Right? And then the legal structure deals with the divvying out of the investors' interests in that commingled vehicle. In the SMA, that's not the case. I'm dropping the trades right into the client's account, which means I don't have one big pool of assets. I have N number of pools of assets where N is equal to the number of accounts and clients that I have. And sometimes clients have more than one account. I mean, in the high net worth space, we can sign up one client and they show up. We can sign up with six different trusts. Right? So it's not even one client. It's six clients in a sense. So the tools out there to manage that at scale are non-existent to terrible. There's just no good answers if you're the manager. And if you're trading options, it's even worse. There basically is no answer. So we just put our thinking caps on a few years ago and we built our own. We conceived of and coded the entire asset management back end. That we run our business on from trade staging and pre-compliance checks and model management to trade reconciliation on to our entire trade staging platform. And then we collect files from custodians, run reconciliations, do our P&L right down to generating our billing. Right? We had to code it all because we had to be able to deal with a complex hierarchy of accounts across many custodians. So it's harder. The bottom line. Right? Now Zed has the investment background and I also, kind of by chance, have the technology background and I've written code in previous jobs. So we were able to do it. So we invented this thing that allows us to run SMAs at scale within derivatives in a very highly controlled, like there's a lot of risk controls and a lot of risk management and control functions that govern all of this that we've had to create around them. But we did it. That's just beyond... The idea that an asset manager of any size is going to just start from scratch and build one of these systems. If you've ever worked in one of these firms or worked in IT at one of these firms, it's just not possible. So to some extent, being a startup business two and a half years ago and starting from an empty AWS account and a blank screen of Python was a real advantage in that we've created now a tool that effectively solves all of these problems. We're currently running many mandates across six custodians and we can do it with three people and no stress. But that piece of technology and being able to trade and allocate across multiple clients with multiple accounts at multiple custodians and then reconcile it and then do the P&L reporting and the billing, every problem that you have as a hedge fund is multiplied by the number of accounts that you have instead of just one vehicle. And for the most part, people aren't willing to sign up for that.
